1
00:01:10,353 --> 00:01:11,360
Longing.

2
00:01:13,630 --> 00:01:14,630
Rusted.

3
00:01:15,189 --> 00:01:16,189
Seventeen.

4
00:01:16,815 --> 00:01:17,815
Daybreak.

5
00:01:19,025 --> 00:01:20,151
Furnace.

6
00:01:21,534 --> 00:01:22,534
Nine.

7
00:01:23,074 --> 00:01:24,327
Benign.

8
00:01:25,619 --> 00:01:27,370
Homecoming.

9
00:01:28,371 --> 00:01:29,414
One.

10
00:01:31,333 --> 00:01:32,718
Freight car.

11
00:01:40,905 --> 00:01:42,264
Good morning, Soldier.

12
00:01:44,572 --> 00:01:45,947
Ready to comply.

13
00:01:47,213 --> 00:01:48,600
I have a mission for you.

14
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:52,103
Sanction and extract.

15
00:01:52,938 --> 00:01:54,314
No witnesses.

16
00:02:35,563 --> 00:02:37,083
Well done Soldier.

17
00:03:22,009 --> 00:03:23,301
<i>Alright, what do you see?</i>

18
00:03:24,046 --> 00:03:25,509
Standard beat cops.

19
00:03:27,065 --> 00:03:28,338
Small station.

20
00:03:30,702 --> 00:03:31,828
Quiet street.

21
00:03:32,329 --> 00:03:33,830
<i>It's a good target.</i>

22
00:03:34,153 --> 00:03:36,280
There's an ATM on the south corner,
which means?

23
00:03:36,291 --> 00:03:37,334
Cameras.

24
00:03:37,500 --> 00:03:39,044
<i>Both cross streets are one-way.</i>

25
00:03:39,336 --> 00:03:41,081
So, compromised escape routes.

26
00:03:41,671 --> 00:03:43,524
Means our guy doesn't
care about being seen.

27
00:03:43,548 --> 00:03:45,534
He isn't afraid to make
a mess on the way out.

28
00:03:45,767 --> 00:03:47,767
You see that Range Rover
halfway up the block?

29
00:03:47,886 --> 00:03:49,916
Yeah, the red one? It's cute.

30
00:03:49,989 --> 00:03:51,285
<i>It's also bulletproof,</i>

31
00:03:51,287 --> 00:03:52,610
<i>which means private security,</i>

32
00:03:52,612 --> 00:03:53,830
<i>which means more guns,</i>

33
00:03:53,832 --> 00:03:56,078
<i>which means more headaches
for somebody, probably us.</i>

34
00:03:56,561 --> 00:03:59,064
You guys know I can move things
with my mind, right?

35
00:03:59,309 --> 00:04:01,523
Looking over your shoulder
needs to become second nature.

36
00:04:02,484 --> 00:04:04,861
Anybody ever tell you
you're a little paranoid?

37
00:04:04,945 --> 00:04:05,973
<i>Not to my face.</i>

38
00:04:05,975 --> 00:04:07,337
<i>Why? Did you hear something?</i>

39
00:04:07,364 --> 00:04:08,614
<i>Eyes on target, folks.</i>

40
00:04:09,012 --> 00:04:10,888
This is the best lead we've had
on Rumlow in six months.

41
00:04:10,902 --> 00:04:12,017
I don't want to lose him.

42
00:04:12,275 --> 00:04:14,213
If he sees us coming,
that won't be a problem.

43
00:04:14,306 --> 00:04:15,640
He kind of hates us.

44
00:04:19,209 --> 00:04:20,081
Sam.

45
00:04:20,194 --> 00:04:21,612
See that garbage truck?

46
00:04:22,045 --> 00:04:23,154
Tag it.

47
00:04:41,846 --> 00:04:42,930
Give me X-ray.

48
00:04:48,071 --> 00:04:49,739
<i>That truck's loaded for max weight.</i>

49
00:04:49,948 --> 00:04:50,948
And the driver's armed.

50
00:04:51,089 --> 00:04:52,302
It's a battering ram.

51
00:04:52,304 --> 00:04:53,305
<i>Go now.</i>
What?

52
00:04:54,452 --> 00:04:55,564
He's not hitting the police.

53
00:05:59,851 --> 00:06:01,770
Body Armour, AR-15s.

54
00:06:01,978 --> 00:06:03,247
<i>I make seven hostiles.</i>

55
00:06:12,322 --> 00:06:13,417
I make five.

56
00:06:19,309 --> 00:06:19,921
Sam.

57
00:06:23,807 --> 00:06:24,561
Four.

58
00:06:29,339 --> 00:06:30,757
Rumlow's on the third floor.

59
00:06:30,840 --> 00:06:32,381
Wanda, just like we practiced.

60
00:06:32,383 --> 00:06:33,423
What about the gas?

61
00:06:33,510 --> 00:06:34,475
Get it out.

62
00:06:52,529 --> 00:06:53,571
Pack it up.

63
00:07:31,067 --> 00:07:32,152
He's here.

64
00:07:35,989 --> 00:07:37,407
Rumlow has a biological weapon.

65
00:07:37,574 --> 00:07:38,495
I'm on it.

66
00:08:13,938 --> 00:08:15,773
I don't work like that no more.

67
00:08:19,115 --> 00:08:20,116
Fire in the hole.

68
00:08:25,622 --> 00:08:26,664
No!

69
00:08:49,604 --> 00:08:50,524
Sam.

70
00:08:50,855 --> 00:08:52,713
<i>He's in an AFV heading north.</i>

71
00:08:57,654 --> 00:08:59,156
Take this to the airstrip.

72
00:08:59,518 --> 00:09:01,625
We're not gonna outrun them.
Lose the truck.

73
00:09:09,385 --> 00:09:11,255
Where are you going to meet us?
I'm not.

74
00:09:23,368 --> 00:09:24,891
I've got four, they're splitting up.

75
00:09:29,936 --> 00:09:31,307
I got the two on the left.

76
00:09:40,029 --> 00:09:41,239
They ditched their gear.

77
00:09:41,406 --> 00:09:43,406
It's a shell game now.
One of them has the payload.

78
00:09:49,289 --> 00:09:50,985
There you are,
you son of a bitch.

79
00:09:52,244 --> 00:09:53,671
I've been waiting for this.

80
00:10:10,807 --> 00:10:11,760
He doesn't have it.

81
00:10:12,520 --> 00:10:13,521
I'm empty!

82
00:10:13,730 --> 00:10:14,981
Out of the way!

83
00:10:54,288 --> 00:10:55,224
Drop it.

84
00:10:56,159 --> 00:10:57,159
Or I'll drop this.

85
00:10:58,775 --> 00:11:00,568
Drop it!
He'll do it!

86
00:11:07,867 --> 00:11:08,999
Payload secure.

87
00:11:09,188 --> 00:11:09,974
Thanks, Sam.

88
00:11:09,994 --> 00:11:10,994
Don't thank me.

89
00:11:11,357 --> 00:11:12,905
I'm not thanking that thing.

90
00:11:12,955 --> 00:11:13,956
His name is Redwing.

91
00:11:13,967 --> 00:11:15,351
<i>I'm still not thanking it.</i>

92
00:11:15,476 --> 00:11:16,636
He's cute. Go ahead, pet him.

93
00:11:23,299 --> 00:11:24,300
Come on!

94
00:11:32,603 --> 00:11:34,780
This is for dropping
a building on my face.

95
00:11:56,874 --> 00:11:58,811
I think I look pretty good,
all things considered.

96
00:11:58,835 --> 00:11:59,835
Who's your buyer?

97
00:12:00,211 --> 00:12:01,604
You know, he knew you.

98
00:12:02,171 --> 00:12:04,215
Your pal, your buddy, your BUCKY.

99
00:12:05,888 --> 00:12:06,888
What did you say?

100
00:12:06,890 --> 00:12:08,300
He remembered you.

101
00:12:09,178 --> 00:12:10,161
I was there.

102
00:12:10,515 --> 00:12:11,875
He got all weepy about it.

103
00:12:13,357 --> 00:12:15,150
Till they put his brain back in a blender.

104
00:12:15,935 --> 00:12:17,649
He wanted you to know something.

105
00:12:17,925 --> 00:12:18,968
He said to me.

106
00:12:19,355 --> 00:12:20,799
Please tell Rogers.

107
00:12:22,024 --> 00:12:23,276
When you got to go.

108
00:12:23,787 --> 00:12:24,997
You got to go.

109
00:12:27,530 --> 00:12:29,181
And you're coming with me.

110
00:12:45,631 --> 00:12:46,896
Oh, my God.

111
00:12:50,052 --> 00:12:50,995
Sam.

112
00:12:51,531 --> 00:12:52,344
We need...

113
00:12:53,222 --> 00:12:54,353
Fire and Rescue,

114
00:12:54,677 --> 00:12:56,096
on the south side of the building.

115
00:12:56,696 --> 00:12:57,873
We got to get up there.

116
00:13:05,193 --> 00:13:11,323
♪ <i>Try to remember the kind of September.</i> ♪

117
00:13:11,908 --> 00:13:15,287
♪ <i>When grass was green</i> ♪

118
00:13:16,662 --> 00:13:19,081
Wake up dear,
and say goodbye to your father.

119
00:13:19,310 --> 00:13:21,130
Who's the homeless person
on the couch?

120
00:13:22,335 --> 00:13:24,420
This is why I love coming home
for Christmas,

121
00:13:24,587 --> 00:13:25,838
right before you leave town.

122
00:13:26,005 --> 00:13:28,257
Be nice dear,
he's been studying abroad.

123
00:13:28,424 --> 00:13:30,259
Really? Which broad?
What's her name?

124
00:13:30,426 --> 00:13:31,561
Candice.

125
00:13:32,261 --> 00:13:33,346
Do me a favour?

126
00:13:33,429 --> 00:13:35,273
Try not to burn
the house down before Monday.

127
00:13:35,275 --> 00:13:36,343
Ok, so it's Monday.

128
00:13:36,368 --> 00:13:39,556
That is good to know,
I will plan my toga party accordingly.

129
00:13:40,353 --> 00:13:41,437
Where you going?

130
00:13:41,604 --> 00:13:44,212
Your father's flying us to
the Bahamas for a little getaway.

131
00:13:44,348 --> 00:13:45,915
We might have to make a quick stop.

132
00:13:45,917 --> 00:13:47,570
At the Pentagon. Right?

133
00:13:48,156 --> 00:13:51,316
Don't worry, you're gonna love
the holiday menu at the commissary.

134
00:13:51,318 --> 00:13:53,354
You know they say sarcasm is a metric,

135
00:13:53,641 --> 00:13:56,435
for potential if that's true,
you'll be a great man someday.

136
00:13:56,437 --> 00:13:57,454
I'll get the bags.

137
00:13:59,997 --> 00:14:02,375
He does miss you
when you're not here.

138
00:14:04,126 --> 00:14:05,237
And frankly,

139
00:14:05,816 --> 00:14:07,283
you're going to miss us.

140
00:14:08,393 --> 00:14:11,193
Because this is the last time
we're all going to be together.

141
00:14:12,577 --> 00:14:14,217
You know what's about to happen.

142
00:14:15,434 --> 00:14:16,852
Say something.

143
00:14:16,889 --> 00:14:18,613
If you don't, you'll regret it.

144
00:14:22,645 --> 00:14:23,703
I love you, Dad.

145
00:14:25,314 --> 00:14:26,867
And I know you did
the best you could.

146
00:14:43,416 --> 00:14:44,852
That's how I wish it happened.

147
00:14:47,837 --> 00:14:49,569
Binarily Augmented...

148
00:14:49,571 --> 00:14:51,500
Retro-Framing or BARF.

149
00:14:51,716 --> 00:14:53,331
God, I got to work on that acronym.

150
00:14:53,460 --> 00:14:55,837
An extremely costly method,

151
00:14:56,083 --> 00:14:57,936
of hijacking the hippocampus,

152
00:14:58,537 --> 00:15:00,302
to clear...

153
00:15:01,479 --> 00:15:02,642
traumatic memories.

154
00:15:06,478 --> 00:15:07,688
It doesn't change the fact

155
00:15:07,690 --> 00:15:09,525
that they never made it to the airport...

156
00:15:10,192 --> 00:15:12,816
or all the things I did to
avoid processing my grief,

157
00:15:12,818 --> 00:15:13,518
but...

158
00:15:15,197 --> 00:15:19,535
Plus, $611 million for my
little therapeutic experiment?

159
00:15:21,537 --> 00:15:23,985
No one in their right mind
would have ever funded it.

160
00:15:25,541 --> 00:15:27,841
Help me out,
what's the MIT mission statement?

161
00:15:28,252 --> 00:15:29,803
To generate,

162
00:15:30,127 --> 00:15:32,381
disseminate and preserve knowledge.

163
00:15:32,965 --> 00:15:34,234
And work with others,

164
00:15:34,717 --> 00:15:37,401
to bring it to bear on
the world's great challenges.

165
00:15:38,554 --> 00:15:41,407
Well, you are the others.

166
00:15:42,558 --> 00:15:45,564
And, quiet as it's kept
the challenges facing you,

167
00:15:45,728 --> 00:15:47,248
are the greatest mankind's ever known.

168
00:15:47,657 --> 00:15:49,373
Plus, most of you are broke.

169
00:15:50,187 --> 00:15:51,686
Oh, I'm sorry. Rather, you were.

170
00:15:52,151 --> 00:15:53,402
As of this moment,

171
00:15:53,569 --> 00:15:55,821
every student has been made
an equal recipient,

172
00:15:55,905 --> 00:15:58,787
of the inaugural
September Foundation Grant.

173
00:15:59,225 --> 00:16:00,288
As in...

174
00:16:00,910 --> 00:16:03,400
all of your projects have
just been approved and funded.

175
00:16:06,749 --> 00:16:08,852
No strings, no taxes, just...

176
00:16:09,430 --> 00:16:11,152
reframe the future!

177
00:16:11,837 --> 00:16:13,206
Starting now.

178
00:16:23,653 --> 00:16:24,654
Go break some eggs.

179
00:16:35,444 --> 00:16:37,335
That took my breath away.

180
00:16:37,780 --> 00:16:39,247
Oh, Tony! So generous.

181
00:16:39,435 --> 00:16:40,391
So much money!

182
00:16:41,701 --> 00:16:42,905
Out of curiosity...

183
00:16:43,819 --> 00:16:46,609
will any portion of that grant
be made available to faculty?

184
00:16:46,611 --> 00:16:47,933
I know, gross but hear me out.

185
00:16:47,935 --> 00:16:50,280
I have got this killer idea
for a self-cooking hot dog.

186
00:16:50,282 --> 00:16:52,647
Basically, chemical detonator embedded...
Restroom's this way, yeah?

187
00:16:52,649 --> 00:16:54,052
Yeah. Embedded in the meat shaft.

188
00:16:54,054 --> 00:16:56,231
Mr Stark, I am so sorry
about the teleprompter.

189
00:16:56,232 --> 00:16:57,756
I didn't know Miss Potts had canceled.

190
00:16:57,758 --> 00:16:59,282
They didn't have time to fix it.

191
00:17:01,011 --> 00:17:02,691
It's fine. I'll be right back.

192
00:17:03,305 --> 00:17:04,473
We'll catch up later.

193
00:17:22,658 --> 00:17:24,899
That was nice,
what you did for those young people.

194
00:17:26,327 --> 00:17:27,403
They deserve it.

195
00:17:27,830 --> 00:17:29,672
Plus, it helps ease my conscience.

196
00:17:30,583 --> 00:17:34,754
They say there is a correlation
between generosity and guilt.

197
00:17:36,255 --> 00:17:38,344
But if you've got the money...

198
00:17:39,717 --> 00:17:41,352
break as many eggs as you like.

199
00:17:42,595 --> 00:17:43,334
Right?

200
00:17:52,730 --> 00:17:53,730
Are you going up?

201
00:17:54,190 --> 00:17:55,826
I'm right where I want to be.

202
00:17:56,979 --> 00:17:57,866
Ok. Ok. Hey.

203
00:18:01,363 --> 00:18:03,964
Sorry, it's an occupational hazard.

204
00:18:04,366 --> 00:18:06,010
I work for the State Department.

205
00:18:06,702 --> 00:18:08,231
Human Resources.

206
00:18:08,871 --> 00:18:10,223
I know it's boring...

207
00:18:10,956 --> 00:18:13,696
but it enabled me to raise a son.

208
00:18:15,091 --> 00:18:18,010
I'm very proud
of what he grew up to be.

209
00:18:19,965 --> 00:18:21,965
His name was Charlie Spencer.

210
00:18:24,929 --> 00:18:26,055
You murdered him.

211
00:18:27,723 --> 00:18:29,097
In Sokovia.

212
00:18:31,060 --> 00:18:33,746
Not that matters in the least to you.

213
00:18:35,815 --> 00:18:37,942
You think you fight for us?

214
00:18:39,151 --> 00:18:41,260
You just fight for yourself.

215
00:18:43,033 --> 00:18:46,158
Who's going to avenge my son, Stark?

216
00:18:47,706 --> 00:18:48,813
He's dead,

217
00:18:49,495 --> 00:18:50,880
and I blame you.

218
00:19:00,130 --> 00:19:03,393
<i>11 Wakandans were among
those killed during a confrontation</i>

219
00:19:03,395 --> 00:19:05,621
<i>between the Avengers
and a group of mercenaries</i>

220
00:19:05,665 --> 00:19:07,709
<i>in Lagos, Nigeria last month.</i>

221
00:19:07,778 --> 00:19:09,615
<i>The traditionally reclusive Wakandans</i>

222
00:19:09,617 --> 00:19:11,611
<i>were on an outreach
mission in Lagos,</i>

223
00:19:11,714 --> 00:19:12,802
<i>when the attack occurred.</i>

224
00:19:12,935 --> 00:19:16,105
<i>Our people's blood is spilled
on foreign soil,</i>

225
00:19:16,939 --> 00:19:19,531
<i>not only because of
the actions of criminals,</i>

226
00:19:19,987 --> 00:19:23,624
<i>but by the indifference
of those pledged to stop them.</i>

227
00:19:23,881 --> 00:19:26,491
<i>Victory at the expense of the innocent,</i>

228
00:19:27,283 --> 00:19:29,228
<i>is no victory at all.</i>

229
00:19:29,446 --> 00:19:31,180
<i>The Wakandan king went on...</i>

230
00:19:31,453 --> 00:19:32,973
<i>They are operating outside</i>

231
00:19:32,997 --> 00:19:34,748
<i>and above the international law.</i>

232
00:19:34,832 --> 00:19:36,041
<i>Because that's the reality,</i>

233
00:19:36,125 --> 00:19:37,710
<i>if we don't respond to acts like these.</i>

234
00:19:37,869 --> 00:19:39,763
<i>What legal authority
does an enhanced</i>

235
00:19:39,765 --> 00:19:41,933
<i>individual like
Wanda Maximoff have,</i>

236
00:19:42,002 --> 00:19:43,237
to operate in Nigeri...

237
00:19:47,720 --> 00:19:48,971
It's my fault.

238
00:19:49,340 --> 00:19:50,270
That's not true.

239
00:19:50,313 --> 00:19:51,545
Turn the TV back on.

240
00:19:51,724 --> 00:19:53,767
They're being very specific.

241
00:19:53,978 --> 00:19:56,803
I should have clocked that bomb vest
long before you had to deal with it.

242
00:19:58,475 --> 00:19:59,778
Rumlow said BUCKY,

243
00:20:01,614 --> 00:20:04,221
and all of a sudden I was a 16
year old kid again, in Brooklyn.

244
00:20:08,908 --> 00:20:10,292
And people died.

245
00:20:12,895 --> 00:20:13,896
It's on me.

246
00:20:14,330 --> 00:20:15,695
It's on both of us.

247
00:20:17,041 --> 00:20:18,217
This job...

248
00:20:21,412 --> 00:20:23,255
We try to save
as many people as we can.

249
00:20:24,256 --> 00:20:25,925
Sometimes that doesn't
mean everybody.

250
00:20:26,050 --> 00:20:28,010
But if we can't find a way
to live with that...

251
00:20:28,177 --> 00:20:29,395
next time...

252
00:20:31,388 --> 00:20:32,838
maybe nobody gets saved.

253
00:20:37,272 --> 00:20:39,438
Vis! We talked about this.

254
00:20:39,474 --> 00:20:41,697
Yes, but the door was open
so I assumed that...

255
00:20:43,984 --> 00:20:46,764
Captain Rogers wished to know
when Mr Stark was arriving.

256
00:20:47,112 --> 00:20:48,572
Thank you. We'll be right down.

257
00:20:49,114 --> 00:20:51,140
I'll use the door.

258
00:20:52,284 --> 00:20:54,320
Oh, and apparently,
he's brought a guest.

259
00:20:54,653 --> 00:20:55,755
We know who it is?

260
00:20:56,664 --> 00:20:58,020
The Secretary of State.

261
00:21:02,446 --> 00:21:03,465
Five years ago,

262
00:21:03,712 --> 00:21:05,064
I had a heart attack,

263
00:21:05,756 --> 00:21:08,472
and dropped right in
the middle of my backswing.

264
00:21:09,593 --> 00:21:12,177
Turned out it was the best
round of my life because,

265
00:21:12,179 --> 00:21:14,306
after 13 hours of surgery

266
00:21:14,308 --> 00:21:15,701
and a triple bypass...

267
00:21:17,101 --> 00:21:20,854
I found something 40 years
in the Army had never taught me.

268
00:21:21,563 --> 00:21:22,731
Perspective.

269
00:21:24,738 --> 00:21:28,617
The world owes the Avengers
an unpayable debt.

270
00:21:29,655 --> 00:21:30,633
You have...

271
00:21:31,281 --> 00:21:32,575
fought for us,

272
00:21:32,981 --> 00:21:34,333
protected us,

273
00:21:34,656 --> 00:21:35,860
risked your lives,

274
00:21:36,453 --> 00:21:39,765
but while a great many people
see you as heroes,

275
00:21:40,249 --> 00:21:41,609
there are some,

276
00:21:43,627 --> 00:21:45,587
who would prefer the word vigilantes.

277
00:21:45,674 --> 00:21:47,968
What word would you use,
Mr Secretary?

278
00:21:48,306 --> 00:21:49,716
How about dangerous?

279
00:21:50,134 --> 00:21:52,871
What would you call
a group of US-based,

280
00:21:53,006 --> 00:21:55,133
enhanced individuals,

281
00:21:55,339 --> 00:21:58,083
who routinely ignore sovereign borders,

282
00:21:58,232 --> 00:21:59,873
and inflict their will...

283
00:22:00,326 --> 00:22:02,970
wherever they choose
and who frankly,

284
00:22:03,226 --> 00:22:05,707
seem unconcerned
about what they leave behind?

285
00:22:10,494 --> 00:22:11,515
New York.

286
00:22:26,003 --> 00:22:27,455
Washington, D.C.

287
00:22:36,061 --> 00:22:37,479
Sokovia.

288
00:22:48,233 --> 00:22:49,401
Lagos.

289
00:22:58,577 --> 00:23:00,204
Ok. That's enough.

290
00:23:02,414 --> 00:23:03,605
For the past four years,

291
00:23:03,607 --> 00:23:05,183
you've operated with unlimited power,

292
00:23:05,185 --> 00:23:06,590
and no supervision.

293
00:23:06,785 --> 00:23:08,953
That's an arrangement
the governments of the world

294
00:23:09,040 --> 00:23:10,884
can no longer tolerate.

295
00:23:13,534 --> 00:23:15,292
But I think we have a solution.

296
00:23:19,645 --> 00:23:21,451
The Sokovia Accords.

297
00:23:22,601 --> 00:23:25,294
Approved by 117 countries,

298
00:23:25,496 --> 00:23:28,074
it states that the Avengers,

299
00:23:28,240 --> 00:23:30,895
shall no longer be
a private organization.

300
00:23:31,119 --> 00:23:32,158
Instead,

301
00:23:32,486 --> 00:23:34,521
they'll operate under the supervision,

302
00:23:34,544 --> 00:23:36,615
of a United Nations panel,

303
00:23:36,909 --> 00:23:39,375
only when and if that panel,

304
00:23:39,800 --> 00:23:41,344
deems it necessary.

305
00:23:42,412 --> 00:23:45,246
The Avengers were formed
to make the world a safer place.

306
00:23:45,791 --> 00:23:47,000
I feel we've done that.

307
00:23:47,541 --> 00:23:51,371
Tell me Captain, do you know
where Thor and Banner are right now?

308
00:23:52,605 --> 00:23:55,065
If I misplaced a couple
of 30 megaton nukes,

309
00:23:55,259 --> 00:23:57,469
you can bet there'd be consequences.

310
00:23:57,970 --> 00:23:59,285
Compromise.

311
00:23:59,574 --> 00:24:00,525
Reassurance.

312
00:24:00,602 --> 00:24:02,206
That's how the world works.

313
00:24:02,432 --> 00:24:03,397
Believe me,

314
00:24:03,774 --> 00:24:05,335
this is the middle ground.

315
00:24:06,481 --> 00:24:09,039
So, there are contingencies.

316
00:24:09,398 --> 00:24:11,879
Three days from now,
the UN meets in Vienna,

317
00:24:11,881 --> 00:24:13,089
to ratify the Accords.

318
00:24:16,405 --> 00:24:17,486
Talk it over.

319
00:24:21,295 --> 00:24:23,828
And if we come
to a decision you don't like?

320
00:24:25,289 --> 00:24:26,874
Then you retire.

321
00:24:50,105 --> 00:24:51,106
Hello?

322
00:24:52,983 --> 00:24:54,543
Is this your car out front?

323
00:24:56,832 --> 00:24:57,995
I jumped the kerb.

324
00:25:00,135 --> 00:25:01,136
Maybe we could,

325
00:25:01,658 --> 00:25:03,100
take care of it ourselves.

326
00:25:03,274 --> 00:25:04,807
If you wanna call the cops, that's...

327
00:25:04,926 --> 00:25:06,597
that's ok too, I guess.
No.

328
00:25:08,665 --> 00:25:09,794
No cops.

329
00:25:11,106 --> 00:25:12,106
Thank you.

330
00:25:49,658 --> 00:25:51,085
You have kept your looks, Colonel.

331
00:25:52,529 --> 00:25:53,530
Congratulations.

332
00:25:57,172 --> 00:25:58,540
Mission report.

333
00:25:58,879 --> 00:26:01,177
December 16, 1991.

334
00:26:01,592 --> 00:26:02,683
Who are you?

335
00:26:04,012 --> 00:26:05,247
My name is Zemo.

336
00:26:07,122 --> 00:26:08,934
I will repeat my question.

337
00:26:09,851 --> 00:26:11,062
Mission report,

338
00:26:11,612 --> 00:26:13,179
December 16,

339
00:26:13,561 --> 00:26:14,733
1991.

340
00:26:15,129 --> 00:26:16,502
How did you find me?

341
00:26:16,623 --> 00:26:18,066
When S.H.I.E.I.D. fell...

342
00:26:19,110 --> 00:26:21,641
Black Widow released
HYDRA files to the public.

343
00:26:22,614 --> 00:26:23,938
Millions of pages.

344
00:26:24,164 --> 00:26:25,365
Much of it encrypted.

345
00:26:25,367 --> 00:26:26,919
Not easy to decipher.

346
00:26:27,301 --> 00:26:28,055
But...

347
00:26:30,627 --> 00:26:31,904
I have experience.

348
00:26:33,166 --> 00:26:34,426
And patience.

349
00:26:36,169 --> 00:26:38,213
A man can do anything if he has those.

350
00:26:39,409 --> 00:26:40,535
What do you want?

351
00:26:41,709 --> 00:26:42,978
Mission report.

352
00:26:43,760 --> 00:26:45,404
December 16.

353
00:26:45,824 --> 00:26:47,242
1991.

354
00:26:47,931 --> 00:26:50,751
Go to hell!

355
00:27:05,532 --> 00:27:08,043
HYDRA deserves its place
on the ash heap.

356
00:27:08,493 --> 00:27:10,424
So your death would not bother me.

357
00:27:11,580 --> 00:27:13,540
But I'd have to use this book,

358
00:27:13,889 --> 00:27:17,100
and other bloodier methods
to find what I need.

359
00:27:17,447 --> 00:27:19,183
I don't look forward to that.

360
00:27:21,173 --> 00:27:22,868
You'd only be dying for,

361
00:27:23,550 --> 00:27:24,660
your pride.

362
00:27:39,691 --> 00:27:42,235
Hail HYDRA.

363
00:27:53,661 --> 00:27:56,122
Secretary Ross has
a Congressional Medal of Honor,

364
00:27:56,209 --> 00:27:57,489
which is one more than you have.

365
00:27:57,789 --> 00:27:59,292
So let's say we agree to this thing.

366
00:27:59,423 --> 00:28:01,281
How long is it gonna be
before they LoJack us

367
00:28:01,283 --> 00:28:02,515
like a bunch of common criminals?

368
00:28:02,539 --> 00:28:04,638
117 countries want to sign this.

369
00:28:05,005 --> 00:28:07,552
117 Sam and you're just like,
No, that's cool. We got it.

370
00:28:07,554 --> 00:28:08,762
How long are you going
to play both sides?

371
00:28:08,764 --> 00:28:09,931
I have an equation.

372
00:28:10,607 --> 00:28:11,899
This will clear it up.

373
00:28:12,721 --> 00:28:14,306
In the eight years since Mr Stark

374
00:28:14,308 --> 00:28:15,767
announced himself as Iron Man,

375
00:28:15,769 --> 00:28:19,917
the number of known enhanced
persons has grown exponentially.

376
00:28:20,360 --> 00:28:21,008
And,

377
00:28:21,088 --> 00:28:22,313
during the same period,

378
00:28:22,482 --> 00:28:24,609
the number of potentially
world-ending events

379
00:28:24,611 --> 00:28:26,318
has risen at a commensurate rate.

380
00:28:26,463 --> 00:28:27,714
Are you saying it's our fault?

381
00:28:28,105 --> 00:28:30,366
I'm saying there may be a causality.

382
00:28:32,568 --> 00:28:35,311
Our very strength invites challenge.

383
00:28:35,330 --> 00:28:37,567
Challenge incites conflict.

384
00:28:38,125 --> 00:28:39,166
And conflict,

385
00:28:41,461 --> 00:28:42,931
breeds catastrophe.

386
00:28:44,011 --> 00:28:45,224
Oversight.

387
00:28:47,676 --> 00:28:50,595
Oversight is not an idea that
can be dismissed out of hand.

388
00:28:50,846 --> 00:28:51,703
Boom.

389
00:28:52,339 --> 00:28:53,271
Tony.

390
00:28:53,942 --> 00:28:56,745
You are being uncharacteristically
non-hyperverbal.

391
00:28:56,830 --> 00:28:58,183
It's because he's already
made up his mind.

392
00:28:58,270 --> 00:28:59,447
Boy, you know me so well.

393
00:29:01,148 --> 00:29:03,650
Actually, I'm nursing
an electromagnetic headache.

394
00:29:04,526 --> 00:29:06,914
That's what's going on, Cap.
It's just pain.

395
00:29:08,650 --> 00:29:09,839
It's discomfort.

396
00:29:10,073 --> 00:29:12,293
Who's putting coffee grounds
in the disposal?

397
00:29:12,909 --> 00:29:15,144
Am I running a bed and breakfast
for a biker gang?

398
00:29:21,871 --> 00:29:23,596
Oh, that's Charles Spencer,
by the way.

399
00:29:24,311 --> 00:29:25,209
He's a great kid.

400
00:29:25,264 --> 00:29:28,467
Computer engineering degree, 3.6 GPA,

401
00:29:28,675 --> 00:29:31,328
had a floor-level gig
at Intel planned for the fall.

402
00:29:31,470 --> 00:29:33,999
But first, he wanted to put
a few miles on his soul,

403
00:29:34,181 --> 00:29:36,683
before he parked it
behind a desk. See the world.

404
00:29:36,712 --> 00:29:37,817
Maybe be of service.

405
00:29:39,275 --> 00:29:40,475
Charlie didn't
want to go to Vegas

406
00:29:40,477 --> 00:29:42,124
or Fort Lauderdale,
which is what I would do.

407
00:29:42,147 --> 00:29:44,858
He didn't go to Paris or Amsterdam,
which sounds fun.

408
00:29:45,190 --> 00:29:46,914
He decided to spend his summer,

409
00:29:47,068 --> 00:29:48,749
building sustainable housing
for the poor.

410
00:29:48,751 --> 00:29:50,253
Guess where. Sokovia.

411
00:29:54,239 --> 00:29:55,666
He wanted to make a difference,
I suppose.

412
00:29:55,668 --> 00:29:56,910
I mean we won't know because we dropped

413
00:29:56,912 --> 00:29:59,039
a building on him
while we were kicking ass.

414
00:30:07,422 --> 00:30:09,137
There's no decision-making
process here.

415
00:30:11,705 --> 00:30:12,935
We need to be put in check!

416
00:30:13,344 --> 00:30:15,100
Whatever form that takes, I'm game.

417
00:30:15,639 --> 00:30:17,807
If we can't accept limitations,
if we're boundary-less,

418
00:30:17,809 --> 00:30:19,936
we're no better than the bad guys.

419
00:30:20,101 --> 00:30:22,804
Tony, someone dies on your watch,
you don't give up.

420
00:30:22,806 --> 00:30:23,676
Who said we're giving up?

421
00:30:23,678 --> 00:30:26,264
We are if we're not
taking responsibility for our actions.

422
00:30:26,399 --> 00:30:28,076
This document just shifts the blame.

423
00:30:28,078 --> 00:30:29,446
I'm sorry, Steve that...

424
00:30:30,268 --> 00:30:31,901
that is dangerously arrogant.

425
00:30:31,979 --> 00:30:34,159
This is the United Nations
we're talking about.

426
00:30:34,180 --> 00:30:36,533
It's not the World Security Council,

427
00:30:36,535 --> 00:30:37,929
it's not S.H.I.E.I.D., it's not HYDRA.

428
00:30:37,931 --> 00:30:39,327
No, but it's run by people

429
00:30:39,329 --> 00:30:40,705
with agendas, and agendas change.

430
00:30:40,754 --> 00:30:42,648
That's good. That's why I'm here.

431
00:30:42,650 --> 00:30:45,400
When I realised what my weapons
were capable of in the wrong hands,

432
00:30:45,650 --> 00:30:47,260
I shut it down
and stopped manufacturing.

433
00:30:47,262 --> 00:30:49,548
Tony, you chose to do that.

434
00:30:49,631 --> 00:30:52,211
If we sign this, we surrender
our right to choose.

435
00:30:53,552 --> 00:30:56,030
What if this panel sends us somewhere
we don't think we should go?

436
00:30:56,054 --> 00:30:57,470
What if there is somewhere
we need to go

437
00:30:57,472 --> 00:30:58,473
and they don't let us?

438
00:30:58,904 --> 00:31:00,225
We may not be perfect but,

439
00:31:00,426 --> 00:31:02,054
the safest hands are still our own.

440
00:31:02,185 --> 00:31:04,350
If we don't do this now,

441
00:31:04,688 --> 00:31:06,110
it's gonna be done to us later.

442
00:31:06,523 --> 00:31:08,336
That's the fact. That won't be pretty.

443
00:31:08,357 --> 00:31:09,584
You're saying they'll come for me.

444
00:31:09,859 --> 00:31:11,090
We would protect you.

445
00:31:11,319 --> 00:31:12,480
Maybe Tony's right.

446
00:31:14,293 --> 00:31:17,909
If we have one hand on the wheel,
we can still steer.

447
00:31:18,255 --> 00:31:20,041
If we take it off...
Aren't you the same woman

448
00:31:20,043 --> 00:31:22,389
who told the government
to kiss her ass a few years ago?

449
00:31:22,391 --> 00:31:23,184
I'm just...

450
00:31:23,762 --> 00:31:24,933
reading the terrain.

451
00:31:25,041 --> 00:31:26,268
We have made,

452
00:31:26,644 --> 00:31:28,313
some very public mistakes.

453
00:31:28,651 --> 00:31:30,239
We need to win their trust back.

454
00:31:30,241 --> 00:31:31,317
Focus up. I'm sorry.

455
00:31:31,319 --> 00:31:33,657
Did I just mishear you,
or did you agree with me?

456
00:31:33,881 --> 00:31:34,986
I want to take it back now.

457
00:31:35,010 --> 00:31:36,010
No, no you can't retract it.

458
00:31:36,094 --> 00:31:37,978
Thank you. Unprecedented.

459
00:31:38,956 --> 00:31:41,347
Ok. Case closed. I win.

460
00:31:42,851 --> 00:31:43,984
I have to go.

461
00:32:26,227 --> 00:32:29,885
And now, I would like
to invite Sharon Carter

462
00:32:30,238 --> 00:32:31,823
to come up and say a few words.

463
00:32:45,121 --> 00:32:48,211
Margaret Carter was known to most
as a founder of S.H.I.E.I.D,

464
00:32:49,292 --> 00:32:51,378
but I just knew her as Aunt Peggy.

465
00:32:53,755 --> 00:32:55,746
She had a photograph in her office.

466
00:32:55,882 --> 00:32:58,511
Aunt Peggy standing next to JFK.

467
00:33:00,128 --> 00:33:01,596
As a kid, that was pretty cool.

468
00:33:01,888 --> 00:33:03,848
But it was a lot to live up to.

469
00:33:04,379 --> 00:33:06,768
Which is why I never told
anyone we were related.

470
00:33:08,186 --> 00:33:10,364
I asked her once how she managed

471
00:33:10,397 --> 00:33:13,540
to master diplomacy and espionage,
in a time when,

472
00:33:13,920 --> 00:33:16,415
no one wanted to see
a woman succeed at either.

473
00:33:17,352 --> 00:33:19,210
She said compromise where you can.

474
00:33:20,150 --> 00:33:21,250
But where you can't,

475
00:33:22,057 --> 00:33:22,861
don't.

476
00:33:24,160 --> 00:33:25,310
Even if everyone,

477
00:33:25,711 --> 00:33:27,903
is telling you that something wrong,

478
00:33:28,317 --> 00:33:29,412
is something right.

479
00:33:29,993 --> 00:33:32,775
Even if the whole world
is telling you to move,

480
00:33:33,306 --> 00:33:34,585
it is your duty,

481
00:33:35,350 --> 00:33:36,882
to plant yourself like a tree,

482
00:33:37,267 --> 00:33:39,089
look them in the eye and say no,

483
00:33:40,059 --> 00:33:41,010
you move.

484
00:33:53,273 --> 00:33:54,693
When I came out of the ice,

485
00:33:55,483 --> 00:33:57,263
I thought everyone
I had known was gone.

486
00:33:58,611 --> 00:34:00,314
Then I found out she was alive.

487
00:34:01,781 --> 00:34:03,324
I was just lucky to have her.

488
00:34:03,950 --> 00:34:05,375
She had you back, too.

489
00:34:07,871 --> 00:34:09,205
Who else signed?

490
00:34:10,081 --> 00:34:12,876
Tony, Rhodey, Vision.

491
00:34:13,793 --> 00:34:14,794
Clint?

492
00:34:15,775 --> 00:34:16,956
Says he's retired.

493
00:34:17,238 --> 00:34:19,174
Wanda?
TBD.

494
00:34:20,800 --> 00:34:23,511
I'm off to Vienna
for the signing of the Accords.

495
00:34:23,762 --> 00:34:25,305
There's plenty of room on the jet.

496
00:34:29,184 --> 00:34:32,020
Just because it's the path
of least resistance,

497
00:34:32,022 --> 00:34:33,963
doesn't mean it's the wrong path.

498
00:34:34,412 --> 00:34:37,005
Staying together is more important
than how we stay together.

499
00:34:38,318 --> 00:34:39,879
What are we giving up to do it?

500
00:34:44,657 --> 00:34:45,810
I'm sorry, Nat.

501
00:34:46,455 --> 00:34:47,654
I can't sign it.

502
00:34:49,245 --> 00:34:50,078
I know.

503
00:34:52,665 --> 00:34:54,083
Then what are you doing here?

504
00:34:56,920 --> 00:34:58,690
I didn't want you to be alone.

505
00:35:05,970 --> 00:35:07,180
Come here.

506
00:35:12,727 --> 00:35:15,011
At a special United Nations conference,

507
00:35:15,730 --> 00:35:18,274
117 countries have come together

508
00:35:18,276 --> 00:35:20,522
to ratify the Sokovia Accords.

509
00:35:25,096 --> 00:35:26,556
Excuse me, Ms Romanoff?

510
00:35:26,616 --> 00:35:28,336
Yes?
These need your signature.

511
00:35:29,911 --> 00:35:31,246
Thank you.
Thanks.

512
00:35:32,372 --> 00:35:35,270
I suppose neither of us
is used to the spotlight.

513
00:35:36,126 --> 00:35:36,740
Well,

514
00:35:37,232 --> 00:35:39,083
it's not always so flattering.

515
00:35:39,266 --> 00:35:41,401
You seem to be doing alright so far.

516
00:35:42,252 --> 00:35:44,382
Considering your last trip
to Capitol Hill,

517
00:35:44,676 --> 00:35:47,790
I would not think you'd be particularly
comfortable in this company.

518
00:35:48,185 --> 00:35:49,118
Well, I'm not.

519
00:35:49,472 --> 00:35:52,143
And that alone makes me glad
you are here, Ms Romanoff.

520
00:35:52,556 --> 00:35:54,220
Why? You don't approve of all this?

521
00:35:54,222 --> 00:35:55,511
The Accords, yes.

522
00:35:55,978 --> 00:35:57,713
The politics, not really.

523
00:35:58,189 --> 00:36:01,655
Two people in a room can get
more done than a hundred.

524
00:36:01,823 --> 00:36:04,159
Unless you need to move a piano.

525
00:36:04,576 --> 00:36:05,843
Father.
Son.

526
00:36:06,578 --> 00:36:07,621
Ms Romanoff.

527
00:36:07,639 --> 00:36:08,622
King T'Chaka.

528
00:36:08,624 --> 00:36:11,495
Please, allow me to apologise
for what happened in Nigeria.

529
00:36:12,097 --> 00:36:12,987
Thank you.

530
00:36:13,765 --> 00:36:15,874
Thank you for agreeing to all of this.

531
00:36:16,165 --> 00:36:19,294
I'm sad to hear that Captain Rogers
will not be joining us today.

532
00:36:20,056 --> 00:36:20,802
Yes, so am I.

533
00:36:20,804 --> 00:36:22,364
<i>If everyone could please be seated.</i>

